  "prompt": "What is gender performativity?",
  "response": "Gender performativity is a theory primarily developed by philosopher Judith Butler that suggests gender is not an innate, fixed characteristic, but a social construct that is continuously created and reinforced through repeated actions, behaviors, and performances. Key points include:\n\n1. Gender is not biological, but a series of learned and performed social practices\n\n2. People \"do\" gender through repeated gestures, behaviors, and presentations that align with societal expectations\n\n3. These performances are shaped by cultural norms and power structures\n\n4. Gender is not something one inherently is, but something one does and enacts\n\n5. Performativity challenges the idea of fixed, binary gender categories\n\n6. It emphasizes how gender is constructed through social interactions and cultural scripts\n\n7. Individuals can challenge or subvert traditional gender norms through alternative performances\n\nThe theory argues that gender is fluid and performative, rather than a natural or unchangeable essence. It suggests that gender identity is created through consistent repetition of culturally defined behaviors and expressions associated with masculinity or femininity.",
